                Born in 2004 and grown up in Wuhan, China, I spent my 18 years of life in my hometown. I entered 
                <a href="https://www.whbc2000.com/">Wuhan Britain-China School</a> before coming to America. 
            </p>
            <p style="            margin-left: 15%;
            margin-right: 40%;
            width: 45%;">
                During high school, I start to become interested in Chemistry, especially inorganic chemistry, as I was amazed by the delicate brace made
                for my scoliosis rehabilitation. 
                As I learned more about college inorganic chemistry, I felt aroused by inorganic chemistry's subfield materals chemistry which drove me 
                to apply to Rice University which is known for its Smalley-Curl Institute. 
            </p>
            <p style="            margin-left: 40%;
            margin-right: 15%;
            width: 45%;
            text-align: right;">

                Though starting out to be a materials chemistry researcher, I felt physics could better explain the inner logic of chemistry and help me find source of scoliosis. Meanwhile, when I found difficulty disposing 
                research data in the lab and impressed by the language processing machine developed by Keda Xunfei during a visit, I realized the importance of 
                data science. Thus, I changed my focus from a chemistry student to a physics+datasci student. However, I would always contribute to 
                the chemistry club as it marks one of my most memorable experience in terms of exploring natural sciences with friends of similar curiosity and 
                promoting the love towards chemistry across the campus.
            </p>
